  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      Motivation: Instead of an infinite sum of power functions, represent a periodic function as an infinite sum of sinusoidal functions (music/sound connection)
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Formula for a general Fourier series:
      <me>
        a_{0}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \big(a_{k}\cos kx+b_{k}\sin kx\big)
      </me>
      Euler-Fourier formulas for coefficients:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>a_0 \amp = \frac{1}{2\uppi}\int_{-\uppi}^{\uppi}f(x)\dd{x} </mrow>
      <mrow>a_k \amp = \frac{1}{\uppi} \int_{-\uppi}^{\uppi}f(x)\cos(kx)\dd{x} </mrow>
      <mrow>b_k \amp = \frac{1}{\uppi} \int_{-\uppi}^{\uppi}f(x)\sin(kx)\dd{x} </mrow>
    </md>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      This all works because:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> \int_{-\uppi}^{\uppi}\sin(kx)\cos(nx)\dd{x} \amp = 0 \quad \text{for all }n,k </mrow>
      <mrow> \int_{-\uppi}^{\uppi}\cos(kx)\cos(nx)\dd{x} \amp = \uppi\delta_{nk} </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Can use trig integrals to show this!
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Fourier Convergence Theorem (wording from Smith/Minton):
      <theorem>
        <title>Fourier Convergence Theorem</title>
        
        
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>f</m> is periodic of period <m>2l</m> and that <m>f</m> and <m>f'</m> are continuous on the interval <m>[-l,l]</m>, expect for at most a finite number of jump discontinuities.
            Then, <m>f</m> has a convergent Fourier series expansion.
            Further, the series converges to <m>f(x)</m> when <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x</m> and to
            <me>
              \frac{1}{2}\left(\limit{t\to x^+}f(t)+\limit{t\to x^-}f(t)\right)
            </me>
            at any points <m>x</m> where <m>f</m> is discontinuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      
      If we introduce my notation from the improper integrals chapter, we can rewrite this last expression as
      <me>
        \frac{f(x^{+})+f(x^{-})}{2}
      </me>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Exponential form:
      <me>
        \sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}c_{n}\ee^{\ii kx}
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Square wave:
      <me>
        \frac{4}{\uppi}\qty(\sin x+\frac{1}{3}\sin 3x+\frac{1}{5}\sin 5x+\frac{1}{7}\sin 7x+\cdots)
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Sawtooth wave
      <me>
        \frac{2}{\uppi}\qty(\sin x-\frac{1}{2}\sin 2x+\frac{1}{3}\sin 3x-\frac{1}{4}\sin 4x+\cdots)
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Triangle wave
      <me>
        \frac{4}{\uppi}\qty(\sin x-\frac{1}{9}\sin 3x+\frac{1}{25}\sin 5x-\frac{1}{49}\sin 7x+\cdots)
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Up-down:
      <me>
        \frac{4}{\uppi}\qty(\cos x+\cos 3x+\cos 5x+\cos 7x+\cdots)
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Ramp:
      <me>
        \frac{\uppi}{2}-\frac{\uppi}{4}\qty(\cos x+\frac{1}{9}\cos 3x+\frac{1}{25}\cos 5x+\frac{1}{49}\cos 7x+\cdots)
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Square pulse:
      <me>
        \frac{h}{2\uppi}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{\sin kh}{\uppi k}+\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{1-\cos kh}{\uppi k}
      </me>
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
</section>
